''\n| blank2_name_sec1        = \u2022 Flower\n| blank2_info_sec1        = Himesayuri <small>(''[[Lilium]]&nbsp;rubellum'')</small>\n| blank3_name_sec1        = \u2022 Bird\n| blank3_info_sec1        = [[Wagtail]]\n| blank4_name_sec1        = \u2022 Fish\n| blank4_info_sec1        = [[Three-spined stickleback]]\n| blank5_name_sec1        = \u2022 Insect\n| blank5_info_sec1        = [[Firefly]]\n| blank6_name_sec1        = \n| blank6_info_sec1        = \n| blank7_name_sec1        = \n| blank7_info_sec1        = \n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n| blank_name_sec2         = Phone&nbsp;number\n| blank_info_sec2         = 0241-24-5211\n| blank1_name_sec2        = Address\n| blank1_info_sec2        = 7244-2 Oshimizuhigashi, Kitakata-shi, Fukushima-ken 966-8601\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = {{Official|1=http://www.city.kitakata.fukushima.jp/ }}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n[[file:Kitakata ramen by macyu in Yamagata.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kitakata ramen]]]]\n[[file:\u571f\u8535 (1389928661).jpg|right|thumb|old ''sake'' ''kura'' in Kitakata]]\n{{Nihongo|'''Kitakata'''|\u559c\u591a\u65b9\u5e02|Kitakata-shi}} is a [[Cities of Japan|city]] located in [[Fukushima Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. {{As of|2018|11|01}}, the city had an estimated [[population]] of 47,184 in 16,668 households<ref>[http://www.city.kitakata.fukushima.jp Kitakata city official statistics]{{in lang|ja}}</ref>, and a [[population density]] of 85 persons per km<sup>2</sup>. The total area of the city was {{convert|554.63|sqkm|sqmi}}. . Kitakata was once written '\u5317\u65b9', which meant 'northern place'.<ref name=\"Fukushima Today & Tomorrow, page 18\">{{Citation| last=Takeda | first=Toru | last2=Hishinuma  | first2=Tomio | last3=Oguma| first3=Chiyoichi | last4=Takiguchi | first4=R. | title=Fukushima Today & Tomorrow | publication-place=Tokyo | publisher=Kenkyusha | date=December 20, 1991 | edition=1st | page=18 | pages= | isbn =4-327-76309-8 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nKitakata is located at the far northern [[Aizu]] region of Fukushima Prefecture, bordered by [[Yamagata Prefecture]] to the north and [[Niigata Prefecture]] to the west.\n*Mountains: [[Mount Bandai]], [[Mount Iide]]\n*Rivers: Aga River, [[Tadami River]]\n\n===Neighboring municipalities===\nFukushima Prefecture\n*[[Aizuwakamatsu, Fukushima|Aizuwakamatsu]]\n*[[Nishiaizu, Fukushima|Nishiaizu]]\n*[[Kitashiobara, Fukushima| Kitashiobara]]\n*[[Bandai, Fukushima|Bandai]]\n*[[Aizubange, Fukushima|Aizubange]]\n*[[Yugawa, Fukushima|Yugawa]]\nYamagata Prefecture\n*[[Yonezawa, Yamagata|Yonezawa]]\n*[[Iide, Yamagata|Iide]]\n*[[Oguni, Yamagata|Oguni]]\nNiigata Prefecture\n*[[Shibata, Niigata|Shibata]]\n*[[Aga, Niigata|Aga]]\n\n==Climate==\nKitakata has a [[Humid continental climate]] (K\u00f6ppen ''Dfb'') characterized by warm summers and cold winters with heavy snowfall.  The average annual temperature in Kitakata is 11.6&nbsp;\u00b0C. The average annual rainfall is 1426&nbsp;mm with September as the wettest month. The temperatures are highest on average in August, at around 25.5&nbsp;\u00b0C, and lowest in January, at around -1.1&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref>[https://en.climate-data.org/asia/japan/fukushima/kitakata-5387/ Kitakata climate data]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nPer Japanese census data,<ref>[https://www.citypopulation.de/php/japan-fukushima.php Kitakata population statistics]</ref> the population of Kitakata has declined over the past 40 years.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Census Year\n! Population\n|-\n| 1970\n| 64,177\n|-\n| 1980\n| 60,456\n|-\n| 1990\n| 59,817\n|-\n| 2000\n| 58,571\n|-\n| 2010\n|52,373\n|}\n\n==History==\nThe area of present-day Kitakata was part of ancient [[Mutsu Province]], and formed part of the holdings of [[Aizu Domain]] during the [[Edo period]]. The town developed as a local administrative center and market town, noted for its [[lacquerware]] and brewing of ''[[sake]]''. After the [[Meiji Restoration]], it was organized as part of [[Yama District, Fukushima|Yama District]], Fukushima Prefecture. The town of Kitakami was created with the establishment of the modern municipalities system on April 1, 1889.\n\nIn 1882, more than 3,000 peasants gathered at the Danjo-ga-hara Field in [[Shiokawa, Fukushima|Shiokawa]] and then marched on the Kitakata Police Station to rebel against the oppression of the prefectural government. Known as the [[Kitakata Incident]] of 1882, it was the first public expression of the [[Freedom and People's Rights Movement]] in the Tohoku area.<ref name=\"Fukushima Today & Tomorrow, page 18\"/>\n\nKitakata Town was raised to city status on March 31, 1954. On January 4, 2006, the towns of [[Shiokawa, Fukushima|Shiokawa]] and [[Yamato, Fukushima|Yamato]], and the villages of [[Atsushiokan\u014d, Fukushima|Atsushiokan\u014d]] and [[Takasato, Fukushima|Takasato]] (all from [[Yama District, Fukushima|Yama District]]) were merged into Kitakata.\n\n==Government==\nKitakata has a [[mayor-council]] form of government with a directly elected mayor and a [[unicameral]] city legislature of 25 members.\n\n==Economy==\nKitakata is a local commercial center. Agricultural products include rice and hops. The area is traditionally noted for ''[[sake]]'' brewing and [[lacquerware]]. Modern industries include [[Aluminium smelting|aluminum smelting]].\n\n==Education==\nKitakata has 17 public elementary school and seven public junior high schools operated by the city government, and four public high schools operated by the Fukushima Prefectural Board of Education. The prefecture  also operates a vocational training school.\n\n==Transportation==\n===Railway===\n[[File:JR logo (east).svg|20px]] [[JR East]] \u2013 [[Ban'etsu West Line]]\n* {{STN|Shiokawa}} - {{STN|Ubad\u014d}} - {{STN|Aizu-Toyokawa}} - {{STN|Kitakata}} - {{STN|Yamato|Fukushima}} - {{STN|Ogino|Fukushima}}\n\n===Highway===\n* {{jct|country=JPN|Route|121}}\n* {{jct|country=JPN|Route|459}}\n\n==Sister city relations==\n*{{Flagicon|United States}} [[Wilsonville, Oregon]], United States\n\n==Local attractions==\nKitakata is well known for its distinctive [[Kitakata ramen|ramen]]''.'' The area within its former city boundaries has the highest per-capita number of ramen establishments in Japan. Ramen has such prominence in the region that locally, the word ''soba'' usually refers to ''ramen'', and not to actual ''[[soba]]'' which is referred to as ''nihon soba'' (\"Japanese soba\"). Kitakata's ''ramen'' consists of rather thick, flat, curly noodles served in a pork and ''[[niboshi]]'' broth.\n\nThe city has over 2,600 [[Kura (storehouse)|''kura'']] storehouses which are now typically used as ''[[sake]]'' breweries, living quarters and workshops.<ref>''Japan'', Lonely Planet (2007) p505.</ref>\n\n==Noted people from Kitakata==\n*[[Uryu Iwako]] \u2013 social worker\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.city.kitakata.fukushima.jp/ Official Website] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://www.kitakata-kanko.jp/ Kitakata Sightseeing Association] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Fukushima}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Cities in Fukushima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Kitakata, Fukushima]]\n", "name_user": "MChew", "label": "safe", "comment": "update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kitakata,_Fukushima"}
